I: Key considerations:
The new office needs to provide high-speed internet for video teleconferencing and large data transfers. I recommend fiber optic cabling as it can handle high speed and the capacity for large data transfers. This would be layer 1, the physical layer, that deals with the physical connection between devices such as cables. Next the data link layer which defines rules and procedures for hosts, will be operated by ethernet using switches to manage MAC addresses and ensuring data is sent where it needs to. The network layer follows which is responsible for how data is routed across networks and identifying hosts, will use private IP addressing to avoid conflicts with public IP addresses so the company ensures there will be enough IP addresses for all devices. Next the transport layer, which handles connections services, will be managed by TCP protocols, which will be useful for video conferencing. Next the session layer, which manages connections between applications. Then the presentation layer which translates data between the application layer and the network, can be handled by encryption protocols. And finally, the application layer which integrated network functionality into host operating systems and enables communication.
Network Hardware components needed include routers and switches for network trafficking, wireless access points for mobility, firewalls for security, servers for internal services, and video conferencing equipment.
II: Lan topology: 
Possible LAN topologies:
1.	Bus topology: All devices are connected to a single central cable. This set-up is cost-efficient and simple to set up, but you start to see performance issues as more devices get added and it’s more vulnerable to cable failures.
2.	Ring topology: Devices are connected to a circular line of cables. This set-up is more vulnerable to disruptions as if a single connection fails it’s difficult to find as you must go to each cable to figure out what’s causing the problem. 
3.	Star topology: Dives all connect to a single hub or switch. This set-up is easy to manage and expand, and a failure to one device doesn’t affect the rest of the network. However, depending on one single hub can cause all devices to fail if there’s an issue. 
4.	Mesh topology: Each device has multiple paths connecting to each other. It has higher reliability and performance as it has multiple paths for data to travel. However, it is higher cost and more complex to set up.
5.	Hybrid topology: Combines two or topologies together to take advantage of the different strengths each one can offer. However, it can be complex to design and manage correctly. 
 Recommendation: I recommend a mesh topology for the office. As each device is connected to each other by multiple paths if one fails it doesn’t stop the network since data has traveled down another route. It reduces congestion as data can travel through the paths more evenly. It’s easy to expand the network as adding devices doesn’t require massive changes to the network. With multiple routes, it’s harder for breaches to disrupt the network, making it more secure. 
